===Phototherapy===
Some dermatologists recommend [[photodynamic therapy]] using [[UV-A#Explanation|UV-A]] and [[UV-B#Explanation|UV-B]] laser or red and blue [[LED]] light to inhibit the growth of ''[[Malassezia]]'' fungus and reduce seborrhoeic inflammation.<ref>{{Cite journal|author=Wikler JR, Janssen N, Bruynzeel DP, Nieboer C |title=The effect of UV-light on pityrosporum yeasts: ultrastructural changes and inhibition of growth |journal=Acta Dermato-venereologica |volume=70 |issue=1 |pages=69–71 |year=1990 |pmid=1967880}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|author=Calzavara-Pinton PG, Venturini M, Sala R |title=A comprehensive overview of photodynamic therapy in the treatment of superficial fungal infections of the skin |journal=Photochem Photobiol |year=2005 |pmid=15629243 |volume=78 |issue=1 |pages=1–6 |doi=10.1016/j.jphotobiol.2004.06.006}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|author=Tim Maisch,a Rolf-Markus Szeimies,a Giulio Jori*b and Christoph Abels |title=Antibacterial photodynamic therapy in dermatology |year=2004 [http://www.rsc.org/delivery/_ArticleLinking/DisplayArticleForFree.cfm?doi=b407622b&JournalCode=PP]}}</ref>

