*''[[Boswellia serrata]]'' extracts: [[Boswellic acid]] has  anti-inflammatory properties.<ref>{{Cite journal |last1=Ammon |first1=HP   |last2=Safayhi |first2=H. |last3=Mack |first3=T. |last4=Sabieraj |first4=J. |title=Mechanism of antiinflammatory actions of curcumine and boswellic acids. |journal=J Ethnopharmacol |volume=38(2-3) |pages=113–9 |year=1993}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |last1=Banno |first1=N. |last2=Akihisa |first2=T. |last3=Yasukawa |first3=K. |last4=Tokuda |first4=H. |last5=Tabata |first5=K. |last6=Nakamura |first6=Y. |last7=Nishimura |first7=R.  |last8=Kimura |first8= Y. |last9=Suzuki |first9=T. |title=Anti-inflammatory activities of the triterpene acids from the resin of Boswellia carteri |journal=J Ethnopharmacol |year=2006 |doi=10.1016/j.jep.2006.03.006 |volume=107 |issue=2 |pages=249–53 |pmid=16621377}}</ref>

===Diet===
There is evidence of a relationship between seborrheic dermatitis and intestinal yeast, such as [[Candida (genus)|candida]].<ref>{{Cite journal|pmid=2533189 |year=1989 |last1=Buslau |first1=M |last2=Hänel |first2=H |last3=Holzmann |first3=H |title=The significance of yeasts in seborrheic eczema |volume=40 |issue=10 |pages=611–3 |journal=Der Hautarzt; Zeitschrift fur Dermatologie, Venerologie, und verwandte Gebiete}}</ref> An antifungal diet consisting of the elimination of sugar and increasing vegetable intake should reduce seborrheic dermatitis.<ref>{{Cite journal|pmid=2556862 |year=1989 |last1=Putzier |first1=E |title=Dermatomycoses and an antifungal diet |volume=139 |issue=15–16 |pages=379–80 |journal=Wiener medizinische Wochenschrift (1946)}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|pmid=2939630 |year=1986 |last1=Menzel |first1=I |last2=Holzmann |first2=H |title=Reflections on seborrheic scalp eczema and psoriasis capillitii in relation to intestinal mycoses |volume=61 |issue=7 |pages=451–4 |journal=Zeitschrift fur Hautkrankheiten}}</ref> {{Unreliable sources|date=November 2012}}

== Prevention ==
A clean scalp is essential to preventing a flare-up of seborrhoeic dermatitis. Daily use of an over-the-counter or prescription anti-fungal shampoo is recommended.<ref>{{citation|date=April 1, 2012}}</ref>

Both natural and artificial UV radiation curbs the growth of Malassezia yeast.<ref name="the effect of UV-light-ADV">{{cite journal|last=Wikler|first=JR.|coauthors=Janssen N., Bruynzeel DP., Nieboer C.|year=1990|title=The effect of UV-light on pityrosporum yeasts: ultrastructural changes and inhibition of growth|journal=Acta dermato-venereologica|location=Stockholm|volume=70|pages=69–71|pmid=1967880|issue=1 }}</ref> Low humidity also inhibits yeast growth. A low buzz cut allows air and sun to readily reach affected areas of the scalp.

